scripts.name: pseudo_ipd
scripts.text:
## # Generate Pseudo-IPD

## ### Summary

## To generate pseudo-IPD, enter digitized survival data into the "digitized_survival" table, enter numbers at risk into the "digitized_nrisk" table, and then run this script.

## ### Digitized KM vs. Pseudo IPD

## This figure below shows the original digitized KM (red) vs. the KM derived from the generated pseudo-IPD. If the two match closely, the generated pseudo IPD can be used. If there are significant discrpenacies, then the digitization should be redone.

#+ echo=F,results=F
suppressMessages(library(plyr, pos = 9999))
library(dplyr)
suppressMessages(library(openxlsx))
library(reconIPD)
library(knitr)

#+ echo=F,results=T
ipd <- reconIPD(surv = digitized_survival, risk = digitized_nrisk,events="NA")
legend("topright", legend=c("KM","IPD"),
       col=c("red", "blue"), lty=1, cex=1)

## ### Generated Pseudo-IPD

## To use the generated Pseudo-IPD, copy the table below and paste into a new table in the Tables Page.
#+ echo=F
kable(ipd, digits = 2)

scripts.name: curve_fitting
scripts.text:
## ___

## # Curve Fitting

## This script is used to fit parametric models for PFS & OS.


#+ echo = FALSE, results = FALSE, message = FALSE
# load necessary libraries
library(tibble)
library(survival)
library(flexsurv)
library(flexsurvcure)
library(ggplot2)
library(purrr)
library(knitr)

# Function to Fit and Plot Models

fitCurves <- function(data, times, unit) {

    formula <- Surv(time, flag)~1

    # KM
    km<-survfit(formula,data=data)
    km_surv <- data.frame(time = km$time, est = km$surv)
    
    # Exponential
    exp <- flexsurvreg(formula, data = data, dist = "exp")
    
    # Weibull
    weib <- flexsurvreg(formula, data = data, dist = "weibull")
    
    # Lognormal
    lnorm <- flexsurvreg(formula, data = data, dist = "lnorm")
    
    # Log-Logistic
    llog <- flexsurvreg(formula, data = data, dist = "llogis")
    
    # Exp Mixture Cure
    expcure <- flexsurvcure(formula, data = data, dist = "exp", mix = T)
    
    # Weibull Mixture Cure
    weibcure <- flexsurvcure(formula, data = data, dist = "weibull", mix = T)
    
    model_list <- list(
        exponential = exp,
        weibull = weib,
        lognormal = lnorm,
        log_logistic = llog,
        exponential_cure = expcure,
        weibull_cure = weibcure
    )
    
    fit_statistics <- model_list %>%
        map2(names(.), function(x, name){
            tibble(
                Distribution = name,
                AIC = x$AIC
            )
        }) %>%
        bind_rows() %>%
        arrange(AIC)
    cat('\n### Fit Statistics\n')
    cat('Akaike Information Criterion is shown for each fitted distribution in the table below.\n')
    print(kable(fit_statistics, digits=2))
    
    model_projections <- model_list %>%
        map2(names(.), function(x, name){
            summary(
                x,
                type = "survival",
                t = times,
                tidy = T
            ) %>%
            mutate(distribution = name)
        }) %>%
        bind_rows()
        
    cat('\n### Fitted Distributions vs. KM\n')
    cat('Survival for each distribution compared with the fitted KM is shown in the plot below.\n')
    print(
        ggplot(data = model_projections) +
        geom_line(aes(x=time,y=est), color = "red") +
        geom_step(
            aes(x=time,y=est),
            data = cbind(km_surv, distribution = rep(names(model_list), each = nrow(km_surv)))
        ) +
        facet_wrap(~distribution) +
        labs(x = unit, y = "Probability") +
        scale_y_continuous(
            lim = c(0,1),
            breaks = c(0,0.2,0.4,0.6,0.8,1)
        )
    )
    
    parameter_estimates <- model_list %>%
        map2(names(.), function(x, name){
            est <- x$res
            tibble(
                Distribution = name,
                Parameter = rownames(est),
                Value = est[ ,1],
                SE = est[ ,4]
            )
        }) %>%
        bind_rows()
    cat('\n### Parameter Estimates \n\n')
    cat('Parameter estimates for each fitted distribution are shown in the table below.\n')
    print(kable(parameter_estimates, digits=2))
    
    model_list
}

## ___

## ## 1. PFS Models
#+ echo = FALSE, results = 'asis'
pfs_models <- fitCurves(pfs_ipd, seq(from=0,to=100,by=1), "Weeks")

## ___

## ## 2. OS Models
#+ echo = FALSE, results = 'asis'
os_models <- fitCurves(os_ipd, seq(from=0,to=36,by=6), "Months")
